    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.59-61_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">59</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Sept. 23, 195<unclear>8</unclear>
                        1511 Dorland S<unclear>t.</unclear>
                        Whittier Cal.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It has been a few years since our last correspondence. Two girls, ages 2 1/2 and the other seven months, have kept me occupied, not counting my wife and job. But &#8212; I have always thought of you and your lectures (I was in your first poety<sic>poetry</sic> classes in 1950) and I shall always have fond memories of your wonderful wife. I have two reasons for this letter</p>
                
                <p>First, I just wanted to let you know that your six words "Be the victor of the moment" have led me successfully through many a confusing business day and have left me free of ulcers. Secondly, one of my hobbies is collecting, or trying to collect, all of your first editions. A friend of mine knowing this, gave me a book of yours which he had found in a trailer camp. A first printing of "The Song of Jed Smith" 1941 by MacMillan.</p>
                
                <p>Inside the cover I found two hand written poems, the careful writing of a woman's hand. There was no name as to the author, but I recognized part of your style. I then presumed since your poetry inspired her, you might like to read two (what I term good) poems from an unknown woman, written I think during World War II.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.59-61_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="authorial">2</fw>
                <fw type="curatorial">60</fw>
                
                I.
                <lg>
                    <l>"Let us accept this moment
                    as the sea</l>
                    <l>Accepts the sunlight of a 
                    summer day;</l>
                    <l>Let us not look beyond this
                    hour or be concerned</l>
                    <l>That it shall pass. Let us not say,</l>
                    <l>As others say who are unwortly of</l>
                    <l>The greatest moment love shall ever know &#8212;</l>
                    <l>"Tomorrow shall see the ending of our love;</l>
                    <l>How shall we bear to see each other go?"</l>
                    <l>Let love be as the cove of some bright beach</l>
                    <l>That holds day long the sun, its tireless lover,</l>
                    <l>Each giving back the warmth each gives to each;</l>
                    <l>Let us so love that when these hours are over,</l>
                    <l>On hearts like <del>the</del> saturated seas when day is done,</l>
                    <l>Shall hold their warmth untill tomorrow's sun.</l>
                </lg>
                
                <milestone unit="section"/><ab>#</ab>
                
                "Window With a Star"
                <lg>
                    <l>"This small still house a woman keeps.</l>
                    <l>See all the lights.</l>
                    <l>A woman's house where no man sleeps these nights.</l>
                    <l>A house without a man in charge stays neat from pride;</l>
                    <l>But the frying pans are still too large</l>
                    <l>And the beds too wide.</l>
                    <l>The attic floors are know to weak in a winter gale.</l>
                    <l>The clock ticks seven nights a week</l>
                    <l>Till the next mail.</l>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26b.59-61_0003"/>
                
                <fw type="authorial">3</fw>
                <fw type="curatorial">61</fw>
                
                    <l><unclear>The</unclear> woman in this house can wait,</l>
                    <l>keep the fires going,</l>
                    <l>With one fresh laundered towel hung straight &#8212;</l>
                    <l>And a star shining."</l>
                </lg>
                <p>I really don't know of these poems were copied or are original. The first poem is rather good, I think, and sounds a little on the Elizabeth Browning side with a dash of the bold Neihardt style.</p>
                
                <p>If you even come to Southern California, please call me. Perhaps we shall never see each other again, due to time, distance and circumstances, but a part of your teachings will always remain with me and within me.</p>
                
                So, thank you for your time, and until then,
                
                    <salute>Your continual friend</salute>
                
                    <signed>Bill Kotoff</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
